==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*fehu'', from Indo-European ''*peku-'' ‘livestock, domestic animals’.  Germanic cognates include Old Frisian [[fia]], Old Saxon [[fehu]] ‘cattle, property’ (Dutch [[vee]] ‘cattle’), Old High German [[fihu]] ‘cattle, money’ (German [[Vieh]] ‘cattle’), Old Norse ''fé'' (Swedish [[fä]] ‘cattle’), Gothic [[𐍆𐌰𐌹𐌷𐌿]].  The Indo-European root is also the source of Sanskrit [[पशुह्]] ‘cattle’, Avestan ''pasuka'' ‘pet’, Latin [[pecu]] ‘cattle, wealth’, Lithuanian [[pekus|pēkus]] ‘cattle’.

